r classic works of late medieval England. The introduction and the translators' headnotes discuss crucial aspects of the texts' histories and thematics, including the importance of the body in spiritual practices, the development of female patronage and of a wide audience for this literature, and the indivisibility of the political and the religious in medieval times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChristian lifexHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500xSources. 0aDevotional literature, English (Middle). 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500vModernized versions. 0aPietyxHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500xSources. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Christian Life / Devotional.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Denise N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartlett, Anne Clark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartlett, Anne Clark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBestul, Thomas H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBestul, Thomas H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKrug, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLogarbo, Mona L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaffner, Paul F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSturges, Robert S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTavormina, M. Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaters, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10